<body>

<div1 type="letter">

<opener>
<dateline>New York City, <date>April 30, 1900</date>.</dateline>

<address>
<addrLine>Mr. C. E. Perkins,</addrLine>
<addrLine>Pres. Burlington Ry.,</addrLine>
<addrLine>Burlington, Iowa.</addrLine>
</address>

<salute>My dear Sir:&#8212;</salute>
</opener>

<p>The citizens of Cody, Wyo., are <choice><sic>verymuch</sic><corr> very much</corr></choice>  alarmed owing to your surveyors surveying a line on the north side of the Shoshone river opposite the town of Cody.  This survey runs from Corbett to the hot springs, three miles above Cody.  Can I assure residents of Cody that when you do build into that country that you will build to Cody?  You know I have spent six years of time and lots of money to open up that unknown country.</p>

<closer>
<salute>Very truly yours,</salute>
<signed>W. F. Cody</signed>

<address>
<addrLine>Address Hoffman House,</addrLine>
<addrLine>New York City.</addrLine>
</address>
</closer>

</div1>
</body>

